A Respiratory Process involves the function of components of the respiratory tract involved in breathing, which include the nose, throat, larynx, trachea, bronchi, and lungs.
An increase in respiratory secretions.
Bronchoconstriction involves narrowing of air passage lumina, typically due to bronchial smooth muscle contraction, and leads to decreased air flow.
Bronchodilation involves widening of air passage lumina, typically due to bronchial smooth muscle relaxation, and leads to increased air flow.
Abnormal decrease of rate of breathing.
Abnormal increase of rate of breathing.
A change from the normal breathing pattern in an infant, child, or adult, in terms of the amplitude and frequency of inhalations and exhalations.
A decrease in ventilation secondary to impaired signals from the central nervous system.

A sleep disorder (insomnia, hypersomnia, or parasomnia) for which there is strong evidence that the disorder is etiologically linked to the direct physiological effects of a substance (i.e., a drug of abuse, a medication, or toxin exposure).
A disturbing dream that occurs during rapid eye movement sleep and results in feelings of strong terror, fear, distress, or anxiety.
A nervous system disorder characterized by diminished responsiveness and consciousness, and rigidity of the body.
A sustained, sudden and involuntary contraction of a muscle or group of muscles.
A sensation of lightheadedness, unsteadiness, turning, spinning or rocking.

An antiemetic effect involves suppression of nausea and vomiting. Emesis is a complex process coordinated by a central emesis center located in the lateral reticular formation of the mid-brainstem. Inhibition of certain neurotransmitters (e.g., 5-HT) or their receptors located in this region inhibits emesis.
Heightened urges of sexual desires in preparation for sexual behavior.
The loss of muscle tissue due to inactivity or disease.
A rapid and repeated body muscle contract that results in an uncontrolled shaking of the body.
Unipolar depression that does not respond to commonly used treatments, typically defined as lack of response to at least two appropriate antidepressant treatments.
A lichenoid and scarring inflammatory skin disorder associated with widespread cutaneous inflammation and irreversible hair loss, which occurs predominantly in women of post-menopausal age.

Lichen planopilaris (LPP) is an inflammatory condition that causes patchy hair loss, mainly on the scalp. It is a form of lichen planus that most often affects women in young adulthood. There are 3 forms of LPP, distinguished by specific patterns and locations of symptoms: classic LPP, frontal fibrosing alopecia, and Lassueur Graham-Little Piccardi syndrome.
Quantification of ruminative style response to stress, characterised by passive and repetitive reflection on feelings and difficulties.
Quantification of brooding style response to stress. It is a subtype of ruminative style response to stress.
Quantification of reflection style response to stress. It is a subtype of ruminative style response to stress.
Frequency of chromosomal aberrations in human peripheral blood.
Frequency of chromosome-type chromosomal aberrations in human peripheral blood (typically resulting in damage to both chromatids).
Frequency of chromatid-type chromosomal aberrations in human peripheral blood (typically resulting in damage to a single chromatid).
Quantification of the level of a generalised feeling of anxiety experienced by an individual, typically measured via a questionnaire.
Quantification of some high level aspect of a metabolic network.
Quantification of some aspect of the transcriptome.
Obstruction of the normal flux of blood within the blood vessel network of the lung resulting in engorgement of pulmonary vessels; frequently precedes pulmonary edema.

Dysphoria is a profound state of unease or dissatisfaction. In a psychiatric context, dysphoria may accompany depression, anxiety, or agitation. Common reactions to dysphoria include emotional distress or indifference.
The process of allaying nervous excitement or the state of being calmed.
